THE TOPOLOGICAL IMPERATIVE: A Network Theory of Multiplanetary Economic Sustainability

ABSTRACT

This dissertation presents a novel theoretical framework for understanding and engineering sustainable economic expansion beyond Earth. Challenging conventional analyses focused on technology or isolated financial metrics, I develop a topological theory of frontier economics that identifies network structure—not individual components—as the determinant of economic resilience and sustainability.

Through three generations of the Recursive Blueprint Method (RBM), I demonstrate that:

1. Historical frontier expansions (maritime trade, Arctic development, American West) succeeded or failed based on emergent economic network topologies
2. Sustainable systems exhibit specific topological signatures: scale-free degree distributions, optimal clustering coefficients, and abundant weak ties
3. The Economic Network Resilience Index (ENRI)—a novel metric integrating topology, gradient coupling, and adaptive capacity—predicts frontier sustainability better than traditional financial metrics
4. Institutional interventions can deliberately engineer resilient topologies by altering incentive structures and connectivity patterns

Applied to space, this framework reveals why current approaches to space economics are structurally fragile and proposes deliberate topology design as the critical intervention for achieving a self-sustaining multiplanetary economy.

